Drive thru COVID-19 testing will be offered on Thursday May 14 ‚Äì Sunday May 17 from 9:00 AM ‚Äì 6:00 PM each day at Bluffton High School.
‚Ä¢ Only 1 person per car will be tested
‚Ä¢ The test will be performed by medically trained individuals
‚Ä¢ The test is a nasopharyngeal swab
‚Ä¢ Individuals will receive a code to retrieve their results via text when available. Most result times are 3 days

REQUIRED:
‚Ä¢ Must be an Indiana resident
‚Ä¢ Must show a valid driver‚Äôs license

ELIGIBILITY:
‚Ä¢ Symptomatic individuals that are also healthcare workers
‚Ä¢ First Responders
‚Ä¢ Essential workers and/or are in a high-risk category due to age, weight or underlying conditions
‚Ä¢ Individuals that live in the same resident as one of the priority categories

post_text:
Dear NWCS Parents/Guardians:
May 22nd will be our final eLearning day and marks the end of the 2019-20 school year for students. Thank you so much for making the best of an extremely difficult situation.

On Tuesday, May 26th & Wednesday 27th, NWCS will host iPad collection days from 12 noon to 6 PM each day.

Parents will need to return iPads to the school where each child attends. Parents will need to bring the iPad, iPad case, and charger to the gymnasium of your child‚Äôs school.

Buildings will set up so that limited touching of objects will be needed. Ossian, Lancaster, NMS, and NHS will send further instructions for any particular procedure that is specific to each building. Please honor social distancing all times.

If you are unable to make it to school on May 26th or 27th, please call Central Office (260-622-4125) and make arrangements to bring the iPad at an alternate time. All iPads must be returned by the end of the day on June 1st.

Subject: ITOWN Free Groceries!

As we continue to navigate through uncertain times and constant changes in our lives, we know that things at home may be getting a little tight financially. Because of the increased challenges during this time, our school system has partnered with ITOWN Church to provide a box of groceries for families in our community.

This program is for any family in need - students of our school system or not. Groceries will be handed out at Bluffton High School at 5:30pm on Friday evening. It will be set up to function as a drive through, so you will get in line and pull through to receive your box of groceries. You will not have to get out of your car!

Grocery boxes are limited and are first come, first serve! See the details below to pick up your grocery box.

When: Friday, April 10, 5:30pm
Where: Bluffton High School Parking Lot

Thank you!
--
Kyle Reinhard
Bluffton Campus Pastor
ITOWN Church
260-402-9943

post_text:
Brief update from NWCS after today‚Äôs Govenor‚Äôs press conference:

School will not return to normal this school year. However, NWCS will have to provide 160 days of instruction to our students for the school year. Our current calendar accomplishes that.

Seniors who were on track to graduate will.

We are still planning to conduct graduation by some method at some time so we will not change the date for it yet. However, we cannot guarantee we will hold in on it‚Äôs original date.

High School credit offering classes for Grades 8-11 will continue to completion for awarding credit.

NWCS will have to develop a learning plan due to the DOE April 17th to describe how we will comply with the State‚Äôs guidelines.

As for a local decision, NWCS inside facilities will be closed for any non-work related activity for the rest of the year.

More guidance will be offered for all of this breaking news in the near future.

eLearning starts back up tomorrow.

post_text: In case you hear rumors, NWCS Bus 29 was hit from behind while stopped at the RR tracks in Kingsland this morning approximately 6:50 AM on the way to NHS/NMS. Two adults and seven students were on the bus. The NWCS staff refused treatment at the scene. The students reported no injuries at the scene and were transferred to another bus and taken to NMS. Parents were contacted and given the opportunity to speak to their child to determine if the student would remain at school today. The driver of the other vehicle was shaken but refused treatment at the scene. Kudos to the students and staff involved for their handling of the situation. And thank you to the first responders, police, fire departments, and others who helped at the scene.

post_text: Yes, we are watching the weather. eLearning appears to be very likely for tomorrow, but we are not ready to make that decision yet. We prefer to make "one call" whenever possible. In other words, we prefer to not call a 2-hr delay when a closing or eLearning day is more likely. So, if we are getting snow later today and we don't call for a delay when other schools do, it is because a delay would be obvious and a closure/eLearning day is being strongly considered. Thanks!

post_text:
Dear NWCS Parents/Guardians,

Flu/cold season is upon us! Our school nurses have worked together to provide some reminders as we all work together to keep everyone healthy!

Please keep your student home if they experience fever, vomiting and/or diarrhea and have not been symptom free without the use of medication for 24 hours. In addition to staying home, please remember to wash your hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds. If soap and water are not available, use an alcohol-based hand sanitizer. Avoid touching your eyes, nose, and mouth with unwashed hands. Avoid close contact with people who are sick. Stay home when you are sick. Cover your cough or sneeze with a tissue, then throw the tissue in the trash. Clean and disinfect frequently touched objects and surfaces.

In addition, please help educate your child(ren) with tips on how to stay healthy and prevent the spread of germs.

Thank you for helping to keep our students and staff healthy!
text:
Dear NWCS Parents/Guardians,

Flu/cold season is upon us! Our school nurses have worked together to provide some reminders as we all work together to keep everyone healthy!

Please keep your student home if they experience fever, vomiting and/or diarrhea and have not been symptom free without the use of medication for 24 hours. In addition to staying home, please remember to wash your hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds. If soap and water are not available, use an alcohol-based hand sanitizer. Avoid touching your eyes, nose, and mouth with unwashed hands. Avoid close contact with people who are sick. Stay home when you are sick. Cover your cough or sneeze with a tissue, then throw the tissue in the trash. Clean and disinfect frequently touched objects and surfaces.

In addition, please help educate your child(ren) with tips on how to stay healthy and prevent the spread of germs.

Thank you for helping to keep our students and staff healthy!

post_text: A big thanks to Joe Elkins for speaking with NMS 8th grade students in Carey Smith's & Eric Morgan's classes yesterday and today. Mr. Elkins used the four Hogwarts Houses from Harry Potter to help students understand their individual gifts and talents. He also encouraged them to think of career areas that might interest them and highlighted Career and Technical Education opportunities available to our high school students. Additionally, he shared the challenges he faced when went to college right out of high school and wasn't invited back for his second year. Mr. Elkins' story of persistence should be encouraging to all of our students. Thanks again Joe!

Dear Parents/Guardians,

We are still in GREAT NEED of canned and boxed food items for our canned food drive. We are also still in need of children's gloves, socks, underwear, coloring books, and crayons. The last day to send in your items is this Friday, December 13th. All donated items will be sent to the following: Northern Wells Food Pantry, Bluffton Food and Item Pantry, and Lutheran Children's Hospital Wing. Any support is greatly appreciated!

Amber Hackworth
4th Grade Teacher
Ossian Elementary

Matt Leach - ABC21 Weather
December 9, 2019 at 4:49 PM ¬∑

Due to recent promotions/departures on the ABC21 Weather Team, we are down a couple of meteorologists. But never fear! We always have you covered :)

Please welcome Norwell High School grad and current Ball State meteorology student Gabe Prough back to ABC21 as a part-time meteorologist!

His live debut will be Friday evening with me on the 5:00 newscast, but you'll primarily be seeing him helping out on weekends, and occasionally mornings. Please give his page a like (https://www.facebook.com/ProughWX) and follow along!

Finally, stay tuned for future announcements regarding our team/weather products as we have some exciting things in store!
